VLet me start with the problem of generalization.
p37
aVGeneralizing from small samples of data is the bread and butter of science.
p38
aVWe poll a tiny fraction of the electorate
p39
aVand we predict the outcome of national elections.
p40
aVWe see how a handful of patients responds to treatment in a clinical trial,
p41
aVand we bring drugs to a national market.
p42
aVBut this only works if our sample is randomly drawn from the population.
p43
aVIf our sample is cherry-picked in some way \u2014
p44
aVsay, we poll only urban voters,
p45
aVor say, in our clinical trials for treatments for heart disease,
p46
aVwe include only men \u2014
p47
aVthe results may not generalize to the broader population.
p48
aa(lp49
VSo scientists care whether evidence is randomly sampled or not,
p50
aVbut what does that have to do with babies?
p51
aVWell, babies have to generalize from small samples of data all the time.
p52
aVThey see a few rubber ducks and learn that they float,
p53
aVor a few balls and learn that they bounce.
p54
aVAnd they develop expectations about ducks and balls
p55
aVthat they're going to extend to rubber ducks and balls
p56
aVfor the rest of their lives.
p57
aVAnd the kinds of generalizations babies have to make about ducks and balls
p58
aVthey have to make about almost everything:
p59
aVshoes and ships and sealing wax and cabbages and kings.
p60
