aa(lp262
VI want to close with just two points.
p263
aVIf you've been following my world, the field of brain and cognitive sciences,
p264
aVfor the past few years,
p265
aVthree big ideas will have come to your attention.
p266
aVThe first is that this is the era of the brain.
p267
aVAnd indeed, there have been staggering discoveries in neuroscience:
p268
aVlocalizing functionally specialized regions of cortex,
p269
aVturning mouse brains transparent,
p270
aVactivating neurons with light.
p271
aVA second big idea
p272
aVis that this is the era of big data and machine learning,
p273
aVand machine learning promises to revolutionize our understanding
p274
aVof everything from social networks to epidemiology.
p275
aVAnd maybe, as it tackles problems of scene understanding
p276
aVand natural language processing,
p277
aVto tell us something about human cognition.
p278
aVAnd the final big idea you'll have heard
p279
aVis that maybe it's a good idea we're going to know so much about brains
p280
aVand have so much access to big data,
p281
aVbecause left to our own devices,
p282
aVhumans are fallible, we take shortcuts,
p283
aVwe err, we make mistakes,
p284
aVwe're biased, and in innumerable ways,
p285
aVwe get the world wrong.
p286
aVI think these are all important stories,
p287
aVand they have a lot to tell us about what it means to be human,
p288
aVbut I want you to note that today I told you a very different story.
p289
aVIt's a story about minds and not brains,
p290
aVand in particular, it's a story about the kinds of computations
p291
aVthat uniquely human minds can perform,
p292
aVwhich involve rich, structured knowledge and the ability to learn
p293
aVfrom small amounts of data, the evidence of just a few examples.
p294
aVAnd fundamentally, it's a story about how starting as very small children
p295
aVand continuing out all the way to the greatest accomplishments
p296
aVof our culture,
p297
aVwe get the world right.
p298
